<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-403-304  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 403 304.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  July 1989 v14 n7 p241(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The paperless office. (distributed PC-based document imageprocessing) (Includes related article on KoFax products)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hough, Dean.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microcomputer-based document image processing (DIP) offers asolution to the problem of establishing the long-awaited'paperless office' by storing, managing, and retrieving real-worlddocuments as computer images.andP;  DIP systems are most useful whenintegrated into a local-area network that provides shared accessto input-output devices such as scanners, laser printers,databases, and optical disks.andP;  Image compression, scanning,printing, and retrieving are among the functions performed bycomputers on a DIP system.andP;  DIP software technology has laggedbehind hardware, but Microsoft Windows, with its standard graphicsinterface, is proving useful for DIP applications.andP;  Windows lacksfree-form image capabilities but can be extended to work moreeasily with raster images by modifying its graphics deviceinterface (GDI) with library routines.andP;  The GDI can be customizedto allow compression of images.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image processingDocument Management SystemsDistributed ProcessingOffice AutomationInformation Storage and Retrieval.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartprogram.andO;Caption:   An idealized distributed document-image-processing system (chart)These code fragments contrast how you display large raster images(program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>